 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udragoon412.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dragoon412</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/26/01 8:56:51 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well...</span><hr size=1> Macnat - <br>
<br>
I don't think archers should have the ability to do more damage overall, just more damage in a very short period of time. I'm not arguing from a reality standpoint, but from a gameplay standpoint. Yes, I agree that a 250-strength troll hitting an elf square in the head with a maul or the like would, realistically, do far more damage than an arrow could (bar the arrow hitting a vital organ or artery). But I'd hate to see this degenerate into a game realism thread, because if it did, it would wind up proving the same points all the others do: nothing. Face it, within game terms, gameplay adjustments have to be made to allow, for instance, a Briton Paladin able to go toe to toe with a Troll anything and have a reasonable chance for success. If you need to justify the arrow damage to yourself in real-life terms, I'm sure the argument could be made that due to the inherant accuracy of the archers, coupled with their tendancy to hit victims who are completely unaware of the archer's presence (negating any chance of dodging) have a tendancy to hit in vital areas or at least the sort of areas that would make combat difficult (yeah, that troll with the 2-hander hits HARD, but would you want to fight when someone just shot a stick tipped with a serrated broadhead arrowhead 50 yards at 200mph and had it lance the shoulder of your swinging arm?). Conversely, the argument, once again from a reality standpoint, could be made that while that 250-strength troll with the maul may hit really, really hard, he's hardly ever going to land a hit. Why? Well, no one's going to miss a troll close enough to hit them with such a close-range weapon. Second, that weapon is so slow and cumbersome, the target could see the troll's attack coming from miles away and have plenty of time to dodge. Realistically, that troll would be lucky to swing once every 10 seconds, and it'd be bloody unlikely he'd land more than a glancing blow on anything that could be described as even remotely agile.<br>
<br>
As far as grouping goes, that's bunk. It's been touted by Mythic for a LONG time that the game would be soloable. Now they're taking that away from some classes and making others all too good at it. They told us scouts are the supreme archers, then made rangers and hunters have the exact same potential witha  bow, in addition to their other abilities. They told us scouts would be great trackers, then didn't give us tracking. They told us scouts could have a climbing ability to let them get into good position for sniping, then they forgot to put a z-axis in the game.  =P So all scouts have now is stealth and the bow, which, by the way, was *supposed* to be the longest-ranged weapon in the game, until the Midtards and those tree-hugging Hibernian faerie people were given bows with the equivalent range. And now, after all that, Mythic tells us NOT to spec the bow and stealth? Think about that... essentially what they're saying is: &quot;Scouts *should* be specced to be gimped mercenaries.&quot;<br>
<br>
They designed the entire class around the bow, now they're telling us not to build our character around that. Why the hell would anyone play a scout and -not- spec the longbow? And for that matter, unless you're planning on regularly having your arse handed to you in RvR, it'd be insane to not spec stealth. That's all we have. Without those 2 skills, scouts are just second-tier fighters. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udragoon412.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dragoon412</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/26/01 10:49:46 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well...</span><hr size=1> One more thing...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub13.ezboard.com/fthedruidsgrovefrm27.showMessage?topicID=204.topic">pub13.ezboard.com/fthedru...=204.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Vinea addressed the issue on another board, but I thought I'd reply over here, since it's little more suited to this board. That is: what to do to solve archery abuse that doesn't involve nerfing the hell out of the archers themselves.<br>
<br>
Many people seem to believe that adding more shield spells will fix the problem, but all this does is relegate crit to being a PvE tool. The archer's first shot is always going to be the most devastating, and negating it, while I can understand under certain situations would be necessary, too many of these shield/bladeturn spells in the game will see archers never using crit on the battlefield. Afterall, why wait twice as long to draw and aim a shot if no damage is going to be done, anyway?<br>
<br>
...basically the way I see it is that everyone's gotta watch their back for SOMETHING on the battlefield. Yes, archers can seem overpowered, but based on what I've seen of RvR so far (watching a friend with a level 32 scout), people are STUPID. They wear bright, obnoxious (and often tacky... people playing this game have no fashion sense AT ALL... but that's another thread...), shoot-me-in-the-head colored clothing, run around with virtually no buffs into areas that scream &quot;you're going to be ambushed,&quot; and then when they get slaughtered by a couple of much more experienced archers, whine that they're too powerful.<br>
<br>
...ironically, if a level 32 mob mopped the floor with a group of level 15 players, no one would say anything, but when a level 32 archer does it, their voices all scream &quot;Nerf&quot; in unison.<br>
<br>
Personally, I just see this whole archer-nerfing thing as the minority of the playerbase screaming really loudly for Mythic to protect them from their own stupidity. They don't want to use tactics or adapt to the strengths and weaknesses of their characters, they just want to gather en masse and (pardon the Starcraft reference) zerg the enemy to death. The majority of players seem intelligent enough to use something that could at least be resemble tactics. The majority of players are smart enough to realize that while the rock-paper-scissors concept of the game (archer beats caster, caster beats tank, tank beats archer) generally holds true, combat is far to situational to apply such a concept universally, and as with anything in life, stupidity conquers all. This isn't archers vs. everyone else, it's the tactically sound vs. the terminally dumb. A smart tank could hand a dumb archer his arse just as quickly as a smart archer would do to a dumb tank. And casters? Pfft... just playing a caster is like an unofficial admission that you aren't too bright...  =P<br>
<br>
So, seriously... what do you guys think -should- be done? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubrairwolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brairwolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/26/01 11:35:35 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well...</span><hr size=1> Yes this was a nerf, however, they were a bit powerful.  That said I feel that any character no matter how you are spec'ed should be able to solo most blues most of the time.  That assumes you are full Health/power etc...  If any character no matter how they are spec'ed can't solo blues then there is something very wrong. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/usaurincotg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Saurin CoTG</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/26/01 12:13:09 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Well...</span><hr size=1> Dragoon stated:<br>
<br>
&quot;And now, after all that, Mythic tells us NOT to spec the bow and stealth? Think about that... essentially what they're saying is: &quot;Scouts *should* be specced to be gimped mercenaries.&quot;&quot;<br>
<br>
Actually, they have always said this, it is just people did not believe them, and with all of the success that archers were having in RvR it is easy to see why. <br>
<br>
Speccing in some melee ability does not make you a &quot;gimp&quot; mercanary, it does however make you a well rounded scout, able to be useful in a variety of ways in both PvE and RvR, rather than the one trick pony that many archers now find themselves.  <br>
<br>
I am not sure just how little most archers realize speccing your bow skill from 35-50 gets you.  You don't get any higher version of critical shot. The only advantage is you get a slightly smaller damage variance on your hits.  Is it really worth it to lose all of those points, all of the other abilities you could have for that? <br>
<br>
Third, I am not sure why archers continue to fully spec stealth either.  Stealth is based on both distance and spec level.  The further away you are the lower the spec level you need to remain completely invisible.  The higher spec you go in stealth allows you to get closer to your target without becoming visible.  So the $64 question is, why do archers think they need to get so close to the target?  <br>
<br>
With 2X level in spec points you can keep a lot  of skills at 2/3 your level and be a very effective, very good archer.  <br>
